Latin America in the Fight Against the Coronavirus
SÃO PAULO/SANTIAGO/BOGOTÁ/MEXICO CITY – The COVID-19 pandemic is a shock of unprecedented scale and unknown duration.
The consequences are already catastrophic.
If we do not decisively confront the crisis, it could become the most tragic episode in Latin American history.
So far, the political reactions in our region have been very different.
Some governments reacted quickly and declared the protection of public health to be their top priority.
Others, on the contrary, unfortunately downplayed the dangers of the pandemic, provided their citizens with false information, and not only ignored scientific research but also disregarded the advice of their own experts.
These leaders chose a populist and divisive policy in the midst of the tragedy.
Latin America's first priority must be to keep the number of deaths as low as possible.
Politicians must focus on improving healthcare systems, equipping hospitals with resources, temporarily utilizing vacant infrastructure such as hotels or conference centers, and significantly increasing testing capacity.
In addition, Latin American states must reject export controls on medical supplies and other critical resources and support additional funding for the World Health Organization (WHO) – in stark contrast to U.S. President Donald Trump, who made a reckless decision to freeze approximately 500 million dollars in contributions to the WHO.
We need stronger global cooperation among health authorities to increase testing capacity, treat and isolate patients, and develop treatment options and vaccines – in order to eventually end the pandemic.
The economic shock is enormous: Not only has Latin American domestic production been disrupted, but the countries there are also suffering from declining export volumes and prices, income losses due to the absence of tourism and fewer remittances from abroad, as well as significant capital outflows.
The supply shock in large parts of the economy could, together with the decline in demand, trigger a contraction spiral.
To prevent this, courageous measures are required to protect household incomes.
This means transferring benefits to the victims of the crisis, including informal and independent workers who do not have access to employment subsidies or unemployment insurance.
Relief for businesses is also important.
Subsidies that help companies pay their wages and wage-related costs protect both them and their employees during the crisis. Therefore, they are crucial for a rapid economic recovery after the pandemic.
If the flood of insolvencies is not prevented, the next victims of the pandemic could be the banks.
And at this point, the payment system—and with it the entire economy—is in danger.
Many companies, especially the small and medium-sized ones, will suffer significant income losses during the crisis.
Without support, the lack of liquidity will soon become a solvency problem.
Tax holidays, payment deferrals, and subsidized loans will not be enough.
This crisis requires not only unprecedented credit guarantees by governments to ensure that banks continue to lend money, but also temporary regulatory changes to promote credit expansion.
Even well-capitalized and well-managed state banks can play a leading role in this.
Generally speaking, although the measures may vary from country to country, overall extraordinary budgetary resources will likely be required everywhere to accelerate the recovery.
Governments must stimulate employment and economic activities without exacerbating the risks to health.
The problem is that the fiscal space in Latin America today is even tighter than after the 2008 global financial crisis.
Therefore, household burdens must be cushioned through budget adjustments in areas of lower priority.
In this context, there is a risk of downgrading creditworthiness, but this risk can be reduced by the governments' promise to correct higher budget deficits within an appropriate timeframe.
However, especially for the small and less developed Latin American countries, urgent external support for budgets and balance of payments is needed.
If both private companies and states take on higher deficits, the balance of payments of the countries are likely to worsen.
The recent capital outflows from emerging markets – one of the largest reversals in the modern history of financial markets – are exacerbating the problem further.
The resulting currency devaluations can have a destabilizing effect.
In many economies of the region, the only way to deal with these mutually reinforcing shocks will be to obtain much more external support.
Here, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) plays a decisive role.
He must take care of the countries' short-term currency and budget needs and continue to support their economies during this crisis, the duration of which is highly uncertain.
For this, he needs more resources and the ability to disburse them quickly.
The Latin American governments should jointly call for a new issuance of the IMF's global reserve currency – the Special Drawing Rights (SDRs) – which should reach a volume of one trillion SDRs.
Although the SZR are assigned to member countries according to their IMF quotas, an unequal distribution could be achieved by establishing a joint pool under the fund's supervision.
Additionally, the IMF could create the necessary capacity to meet the upcoming strong credit demand by immediately doubling the volume of the New Credit Agreements.
And finally, the Fund must improve access to low-cost tools with rapid disbursement—such as its rapid financing instrument—or establish new credit facilities for the pandemic, since traditional IMF credit programs are not being approved in a timely manner.
Large central banks that issue reserve currencies can help by expanding access to currency swaps—either directly or indirectly through the IMF or the Bank for International Settlements, which can channel liquidity to central banks.
Within the domestic country, central banks must utilize all instruments available to them and, if necessary, create new ones in order to provide sufficient liquidity to the financial markets and the economy.
In the end, multilateral development banks (MDBs) such as the World Bank, the Inter-American Development Bank, and the Latin American CAF Development Bank must double the volume of net credit disbursement in the region and tap into highly liquid global capital markets in order to provide further fiscal support.
In cases of exceptional circumstances and in countries without market access, official credit allocation could be supplemented by a debt restructuring.
The MEB should also provide the countries with guidelines on the different policy areas involved in crisis management, including their own estimates of COVID-19 infection and mortality rates – particularly for countries where governments downplay the health threat.
In this context, time plays a decisive role.
The challenge posed by this pandemic is without precedent in recent history.
The world and the Latin American and Caribbean region cannot afford delayed or inadequate responses.
Mutual trust, transparency, and reason remain the best guidelines in these uncertain times – and not populism or demagogy.
The crisis must not be used as an excuse to weaken our hard-earned civil rights.
Instead, it can serve as an opportunity to strengthen democracy in Latin America and to show what it can offer its citizens.
